The latest MSTest version is **4.2.2**. Here are the breaking changes affecting your code:

## 1. `[ExpectedException]` removed in MSTest 4

This is the biggest issue — the attribute no longer exists. Your two tests using it will fail to compile. Replace with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`:

```csharp
// Before
[ExpectedException(typeof(ArgumentNullException))]
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Validate(null);
}

// After
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}
```

## 2. `Assert.IsTrue(true)` triggers warning MSTEST0032

Severity was elevated to **Warning** in 4.0.0. Your `Validate_ValidInput_Succeeds` test will produce a build warning. Replace with a meaningful assertion or remove the trivial assert.

## 3. Test runner change (if using MSTest.Sdk)

MSTest 4 defaults to the **Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP)** runner instead of VSTest. If you stay with the `Microsoft.NET.Sdk` project format (as you have now), you can keep using `dotnet test` normally by just updating the package version. But be aware that `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` is now pulled in as a transitive dependency.

## Summary of fixes for your project

| Issue | Fix |
|-------|-----|
| `[ExpectedException]` removed | Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>(() => ...)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(true)` warning | Replace with real assertion or suppress MSTEST0032 |
| Package update | Change `Version="3.8.0"` → `Version="4.2.2"` in csproj |

Would you like me to apply these changes to your project?
